WEBVTT

00:06.966 --> 00:10.379
All right,
we have Davis McAlary in the house,

00:10.511 --> 00:13.548
famous and infamous
for many of our long—time OZ listeners.

00:13.681 --> 00:15.637
And we have a new voice, Lil Calliope,

00:19.645 --> 00:22.057
Hey, man, good to be here.
Good to be here.

00:22.190 --> 00:24.397
- Me too.
— Yeah. And you're here...

00:24.525 --> 00:27.858
Y'all are here with a new track,
Road Home, which we're gonna play.

00:27.987 --> 00:32.481
- Tell us something about it.
— Right, this is our contribution to a sampler

00:32.617 --> 00:35.825
which marks the debut of a new label
here in New Orleans,

00:35.953 --> 00:37.614
'58 Mercury Monterey Records.

00:37.747 --> 00:40.534
— Gonna drop in a couple of weeks.
- Hmm. Uh, hip-hop?

00:40.666 --> 00:44.409
And brass and funk and everything else
your mama warned you about.

00:44.545 --> 00:47.833
Big Freedia, Katey Red, Ballzack,
10th Ward Buck.

00:47.965 --> 00:50.047
We even got Mannie Fresh
throwing down with us, man.

00:50.176 --> 00:52.667
— Well, who fronts you?
— Uh, that would...

00:52.803 --> 00:54.714
— Sorry.
— Uh... I killed this one.

00:54.847 --> 00:57.133
Split the vocals with Davis.

00:57.266 --> 01:00.599
I wrote, arranged and produced,

01:00.728 --> 01:03.014
but all props to Lil Calliope.

01:03.147 --> 01:07.891
I am awed to be presenting him here at OZ
for the first time.

01:08.027 --> 01:11.895
Well, it's good to represent and present.

01:13.407 --> 01:15.443
Right, brah. Um...

01:15.576 --> 01:17.817
And as you can tell by the title of the track,

01:17.954 --> 01:20.866
we're taking this whole New Orleans
brass—funk—bounce thing

01:20.998 --> 01:22.329
to a place it's never been before.

01:22.458 --> 01:23.823
And that would be?

01:23.960 --> 01:28.579
Musical insurrection. DJ Davis
and the Brassy Knoll exists as political dissent,

01:28.714 --> 01:31.922
and we will not rest until the entire
Who Dat Nation is exactly that.

01:32.051 --> 01:33.882
Because you know what
Katrina made clear?

01:34.011 --> 01:36.423
I'm no longer from
the United States of America.

01:36.555 --> 01:39.262
Right. OK.

01:39.392 --> 01:42.759
Uh, I got a second thing
I wanna lay on you.

01:44.689 --> 01:46.645
A track called The True,
recorded this week.

01:46.774 --> 01:49.140
That's another heavy political statement,
I take it?

01:49.277 --> 01:51.893
— No, no, it's more of a club banger.
— No, no, no, no, no. Yeah.

01:52.029 --> 01:55.942
Me and Don B put it together
and Kirk Joseph worked up a nasty horn riff.

01:56.075 --> 01:58.407
— Check it out.
— Yeah, it's more of like a dance track.

01:58.536 --> 02:00.902
— It's not really gonna be on the sampler.
— OK. Right.

02:01.038 --> 02:02.869
We'll give this a listen later
if we have time.

02:02.999 --> 02:08.915
But right now it's time for the debut of Road
Home by DJ Davis and the Brassy Knoll.

02:09.046 --> 02:11.253
(Music playing)

02:11.382 --> 02:12.963
That was good.

02:18.639 --> 02:20.550
What's he doing here?

02:21.517 --> 02:23.348
I'm the talent.

02:29.567 --> 02:32.149
(Laughs) I love it.

04:04.286 --> 04:06.151
(Man on TV) Start your day out there.

04:06.288 --> 04:09.121
(Woman on TV) Uh—huh. We were talking
about the fact that a picture

04:09.250 --> 04:14.244
is worth a thousand... Then this one, probably
a million words when you're looking at...

04:14.380 --> 04:16.962
- Imagine that.
— (TV) We do have a little bit of showers...

04:17.091 --> 04:18.956
Get dressed proper in the morning,

04:19.093 --> 04:21.334
strap on your shoes,

04:21.470 --> 04:24.303
off to work, like most folks.

04:25.224 --> 04:27.590
(Woman on TV continues speaking)

04:27.726 --> 04:32.561
I'm telling you, it's damn near time
you start putting yourself back together.

04:33.357 --> 04:36.941
Sitting up at night with a bottle
does nothing but kill your next day.

04:37.069 --> 04:41.312
Your sons need to see you wide awake
and fresh when they get up in the morning.

04:42.450 --> 04:45.738
You know how I feel about that goddamn bar,
especially after what happened.

04:45.870 --> 04:48.703
I hate that fucking place,
but I hate you on this sofa even more.

04:48.831 --> 04:50.412
(Slams glass down)

04:50.541 --> 04:51.576
(Turns TV off)

04:51.709 --> 04:54.041
— So what you asking?
- I'm telling.

04:54.170 --> 04:56.081
Either you reopen that bar,
you go back to work,

04:56.213 --> 04:59.000
or we sell that fucking thing
and you bring your ass back up here

04:59.133 --> 05:01.089
and be a part of this family like you should.

05:01.218 --> 05:04.551
One or the other, but either way
I need you up off your ass!

05:08.434 --> 05:12.473
Got a meeting with the district attorney
day after tomorrow, so...

05:14.315 --> 05:15.646
l'll reopen then.

05:16.901 --> 05:18.857
— What?
— Where the hell you supposed to stay?

05:18.986 --> 05:22.194
We closing your mama's house in two weeks.
You can't move no furniture back in there.

05:22.323 --> 05:24.154
— I'll stay above the bar.
- The hell you will.

05:24.283 --> 05:26.490
Then I'll get a hotel room.

05:26.619 --> 05:27.608
Downtown.

05:27.745 --> 05:29.781
On Canal Street, a'ight?

05:37.046 --> 05:39.037
(Door slams)

05:39.173 --> 05:41.539
— Do we know who the judge is, Bob?
— Not yet.

05:41.675 --> 05:44.838
But we did draw Ted Planzos
for the prosecution.

05:44.970 --> 05:47.177
Now, I don't want to be optimistic here,

05:47.306 --> 05:51.891
but my experience with Planzos says
that he's reasonable at the very least.

05:52.019 --> 05:54.806
— Any chance of getting this tossed?
— Frankly, no.

05:54.939 --> 05:58.227
The fact that it's in Jefferson Parish
means it goes forward.

05:58.359 --> 06:01.772
Now, the good news is that they're gonna
go after the kid with the heroin charge,

06:01.904 --> 06:04.236
so if we do everything
we're supposed to do,

06:04.365 --> 06:07.698
they'll most likely allow us to plea
and get probation.

06:07.826 --> 06:09.862
Once you complete your probation,

06:09.995 --> 06:12.031
they'll most likely go back
and clear your record.

06:12.164 --> 06:14.246
(Toni) How about a court date?

06:14.375 --> 06:17.788
Well, for juvenile it's 90 days from
date of offense, so this is good.

06:17.920 --> 06:20.002
It gives us time to prepare.

06:20.130 --> 06:22.872
